SIMPLE: inductive
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inductive
<hw>In*duct"ive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>inductivus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>inductif</ets>. See
<er>Induce</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Leading or drawing; persuasive; tempting; -- usually
followed by <xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A brutish vice,⟦br⟧
<qex>Inductive</qex> mainly to the sin of Eve.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tending to induce or cause.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They may be . . . <qex>inductive</qex> of credibility.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Leading to inferences; proceeding by, derived from,
or using, induction; <as>as, <ex>inductive</ex>
reasoning</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Operating by
induction; <as>as, an <ex>inductive</ex> electrical machine</as>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Facilitating induction; susceptible of being acted
upon by induction; <as>as, certain substances have a great
<ex>inductive</ex> capacity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Inductive embarrassment</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld>,
<cd>the retardation in signaling on an electric wire, produced by
lateral induction.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Inductive philosophy</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>Inductive method</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See
<cref>Philosophical induction</cref>, under <er>Induction</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Inductive sciences</b></col>, <cd>those sciences which admit of,
and employ, the inductive method, as astronomy, botany, chemistry,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inductively</ent>⟦br⟧
